"The oldest profession in the world"

Read below the new editorial of Tattoo Life International magazine
by @mikivialetto 
Recently I happened to listen to an interview on YouTube of a young tattooist who’s been tattooing for less than five years. When asked the classic question, “where do you think you’ll be ten years from now?” his response was that he was sure he wouldn’t still be tattooing as a profession, because he hoped that in the future he’d be able to just give his friends tattoos as something fun to do, like a hobby. He went on to say that he hoped he could “store up” as much tattooing experience as possible, so that one day he might “pour” it into another creative container. What his words conveyed to me is that he believes tattooing is a disposable art form, something to “store up” (as much as possible) and then throw away without looking back, as if it were a launching pad to something better in the creative world. It made me smile, because I thought of other professionals who have given similar answers to the same question. I thought of one person in particular, who does what is considered “the oldest profession in the world”. That expression should have nothing to do with the saying that is often used to define tattooing: “older than time, younger than tomorrow” – though maybe in this case a line may be drawn between the two… 
Read the complete editorial and discover more in the new issue of Tattoo Life magazine 🖤 at your newsstand now! 🤟

This is my Tattoo Life

If you are a tattoo fan for sure you know this man. He is @mikivialetto , one of the most influencer people in this industry. He is the publisher of Tattoo Life. 
He created our history, from the magazine Tattoo Life (a bible for most of you), to the prestigious books series "The Great Books on the Art of Tattooing", up to @londontattooconvention . To be always up to the times he invented the first digital library tattooebooks.com and of course our digital planet tattoolife.com 🌎

But most of all he is a collector of tattoos and his body represents the history of 30 years of international tattoo art. 
This is why from now on we will share with you some of his speeches. Some of them are Editorials published in the different issues of Tattoo Life magazine, or contents you can read on our tattoolife.com. 
Some others will be just short thinks, mottos or what else that are interesting to know.📁📍 Stay tuned and be sure to follow us to be always update on the tattoo industry. 😎

We are in Melbourne, where @samtaylortattoos is ready to guide us through the @empiremelbourne. This is a private studio, where eight tattooists have put down their roots and lit the fuse of their creativity. Each one in his own fashion and without any limits, with individual requests for each artist and the freedom to choose to work at any time of day or night they want. We’ll leave this space now to the protagonists of this article: @bobbydunbar @elriccfh @haydenthompsontattoo @jaketattoos @mattcurzon @mattreidart @samtaylortattoos and @tom_petucco . Here to open the doors for us is Sam himself; we’d already met him when we did an article devoted to him in a previous Tattoo Life. He’ll be our guide as he presents this eclectic family! 
Discover their interview in the current issue of Tattoo Life magazine available on www.tattoolifestore.com

Born in 1912, Les Skuse, lived and died in the port town of Bristol, England. He became the town’s most famous tattoo expert and was almost as well known on American shores as he was at home.
.
He visited the United States in 1956 and corresponded with many American tattooists. He was a big admirer of the Coleman School of tattooing as practiced by Paul Rodgers, Huck Spaulding, Al Schiefley and others...
.
Read more on our website www.tattoolife.com with the article by @pepe_electrictattooing and @minavonb .
#tattoo #tattoolife #tattoohistory #tattoolifedigital #tattoolifemagazine

A popular tag on social networks includes the art of @djangonokes in the dark art category. However we’re not convinced by such a “harsh” definition, because in his works (drawings that look like engravings), Django includes a world of inspirations that draw from his cultural background, splatter and horror movies, metal and electronic music, old postcards and a lot of himself. Because, as he says in our interview for Tattoo Life: “I believe that art is a common good, a fundamental expressive tool which everyone should embrace”.
Discover more in the latest issue of Tattoo Life magazine available on www.tattoolifestore.com .

First and foremost, the Battle Royale is a mixture of styles. A historical tattoo, it came about at the turn of the twentieth century as a result of the meeting of the Western and Oriental tattoo traditions.

It usually shows valorous animals (like eagles, snakes, dragons, tigers, panthers, etc.) locked in a sort of mortal combat from which only one of them will emerge victorious...

Tattooing is the kind of practice that gives so much to both the receiver and the giver. A special magic surrounds the tattooist and person being tattooed, and art comes to life. That’s the magic @__yogi___ talks about in this article. A tattooist from Mumbai, Yogi’s tattoos are developed from Indian divinities, reflections of Mother Nature, and that magical touch which allows him to move his hand on the human body like the rhythm of a mystical and enchanting dance. Spirals, lines and shapes are moulded to this melody, like the circles created by Sufi dancers, who seem to use their bodies to touch the divine. 
Discover the interview in the current issue of Tattoo Life magazine ~ available on www.tattoolifestore.com
.
#tattoo #tattoolife #tattooartist #interview #yogitattoo #tattoolifemagazine

Amongst the current most innovative tattoo aftercare products we find the Protective Tattoo Film by @dermalizepro, devised and produced by the tattoo artist @alexdepase.

Dermalize Protective Tattoo Film is the only certified all-in-one tattoo aftercare solution for the initial healing stage of a tattoo. It's a thin self-adhesive film that protects new tattoos and provides a waterproof, antibacterial barrier that prevents pathogens and external contaminants. 
The film is breathable, light to wear, flexible and stretchable, which allows it to be placed anywhere on the body, also on large scale tattoos (like the one you see in the first picture). It enhances cicatrization and guarantees a persistent brilliance of the tattoo colors.

No more ink dripping, no more repeated washing of your tattoo every three hours, no more missed sport trainings or social events, no more “suffocating” your tattooed skin with useless and harmful cling-film... Just beautifully healed tattoos!

Read the article to discover more: link in bio ☝️ #protectyourart #dermalizepro #dermalize #ProtectiveTattooFilmDermalize#tattoolifemagazine #alexdepase #inkdustry

The beauty and the beast: this is the most recurring image in the works of Russian tattooist @mvtattoo . As he explains himself, his pieces are based on majestic female faces, and are crafted with a style which resembles neo traditional in some respects yet extends beyond that through his use of black and shading. And the beauty and beast, as if they were one, emerge from a secret world.
Discover his interview in the latest issue of Tattoo Life magazine - on sale on www.tattoolifestore.com
